I"—	<h3 id="here-our-model-is">Here our model is</h3>

\[Y=\beta_0+\beta_1X_{1}+\beta_2X_{2}+...+\beta_pX_{p}+ \epsilon,\]

<p>-We interpret \(\beta_j\) as the average effect on Y of a one unit increase in \(X_j\), holding all other predictors fixed. In the advertising example, the model becomes</p>

\[sales=\beta_0+\beta_1*TV+\beta_2*radio+\beta_3*newspaper+\epsilon.\]

<h3 id="the-idea-scenario-is-when-the-predictors-are-uncorrelated">The idea scenario is when the predictors are uncorrelated</h3>
<p>A balanced design:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Each coefficient can be estimated and tested separately.</li>
  <li>Interpretations such as â€œa unit change in $X_j$ is associated with a \(\beta_j\) change in Y, while all other variables stay fixedâ€, are possible.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="correlations-amongst-predictors-cause-problems">Correlations amongst predictors cause problems:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>The variance of all coefficients tends to increase, sometimes dramatically</li>
  <li>Interpretations become hazardous - when $X_j$ changes, everthing else changes.</li>
  <li>In other words, Y should be highly correlated with predictors (X), but predictors (X) should be uncorrelated.</li>
</ul>

\[Y=\beta_0+\beta_1X_{1}+\beta_2X_{2}+...+\beta_pX_{p}+ \epsilon,\]

<h3 id="estimation-and-prediction-for-multiple-regression">Estimation and Prediction for Multiple Regression</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Given estimates $\hat{\beta_0},\hat{\beta_1},â€¦\hat{\beta_p}$, we can make predictions using the formula</li>
</ul>

\[\hat{y}=\hat{\beta_0}+\hat{\beta_1}{x_1}+\hat{\beta_2}{x_2}+...+\hat{\beta_p}{x_p}\]

<ul>
  <li>We estimate \({\beta_0},{\beta_1},...{\beta_p}\) as the values that minimize the sum of squared residuals</li>
</ul>

\[RSS =  \Sigma _{i=1}^n(y_1-\hat{y}_i)^2\]

<p>$=\Sigma <em>{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{\beta_0}-\hat{\beta_1}{x</em>{i1}}-\hat{\beta_2}{x_{i2}}-â€¦-\hat{\beta_p}{x_{ip}})^2$</p>

<ul>
  <li>This is done using standard statistical software. The values $\hat{\beta_0},\hat{\beta_1},â€¦\hat{\beta_p}$ that minimize RSS are the multiple least squares regression coefficient estimates.</li>
</ul>

